Comment: Okay, I know 85% of the comments are thinking that the characters look *"too cartoony"* and they don't match with the environmental backgrounds at all. But has anyone thought why they had to design the characters that way? There are many reasons to come up with that solution and I thought deep into it. For me personally and its not the legitimate answer but, I believe its because Pixar's rendering for this animation has become so great....*it looks like live-action*. I mean seriously,  take out the dinosaurs and you got a movie on a live-action documentary on nature. Like they just went out with their cameras, and started filming landscapes and added CG dinosaurs into them. The *cartoony characters* are the only thing that's making me believe this is an animated movie. .....But man, it so beautiful. I'm diffidently watching this in theaters soon! ^_^

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: While I did mention this on a different video about this trailer, it bears repeating here as well. And before I say my main point, the film does look gorgeous. The details on each of the dinosaurs, to the water effects, to the rock texture, it's technically beautiful. With that said, it looks like the biggest problem with this movie, is the main Dino itself. I myself am not against the idea of having a kid-like Dinosaur as the protagonist, but there needs to be some form of consistency. It just doesn't feel right having lush, detailed, realistic environments being inhabited by a googly-eyed squash and stretch machine like the main Dino. That's not to say that squash and stretch effects are bad, but it needs to fit in with the rest of the movie. Maybe I could look past it if it was just like a side character that comes in for about 2 scenes, but this is the main character! Not to mention the clashing styles of having realistic skin on this goofy character is very distracting. I'm not saying the film won't be good, because knowing Pixar, it'll have a polished script, excellent visuals, and a lasting effect on kids, but I can't help but point out something so distracting.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: While I did mention this on a different video about this trailer, it bears repeating here as well. And before I say my main point, the film does look gorgeous. The details on each of the dinosaurs, to the water effects, to the rock texture, it's technically beautiful. With that said, it looks like the biggest problem with this movie, is the main Dino itself. I myself am not against the idea of having a kid-like Dinosaur as the protagonist, but there needs to be some form of consistency. It just doesn't feel right having lush, detailed, realistic environments being inhabited by a googly-eyed squash and stretch machine like the main Dino. That's not to say that squash and stretch effects are bad, but it needs to fit in with the rest of the movie. Maybe I could look past it if it was just like a side character that comes in for about 2 scenes, but this is the main character! Not to mention the clashing styles of having realistic skin on this goofy character is very distracting. I'm not saying the film won't be good, because knowing Pixar, it'll have a polished script, excellent visuals, and a lasting effect on kids, but I can't help but point out something so distracting.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
I like how many folks are getting uptight about "Hey, dinos and humans didn't co-exist, and it could never happen!"
What if the mass-extinction event didn't occur?  Is it so impossible that mammals could have co-evolved along giant reptiles?  Maybe at a slower pace?  If the dinos are living in today's age, then human evolution WITH competition from them would be set back.. hence why they are only primitives "today" according to this alternative time-line.  Sure, it's highly improbable, but not impossible.  Especially for a kids' cartoon.
I'm more bothered by Arlo looking like an inflatable pool-toy against the environment.  Honestly would have preferred the backgrounds to have been equally cartoony.  But, *art!*, and all that that implies...

Comment:
I do not like the aesthetics of this movie. At all. End of story. Realistic environment with a jellow-plastic dinosaur does not fit. I was reading some of the comments, saying that its to make nature the antagonist, WHY ARE WE ANTAGONIZING NATURE IN THE FIRST PLACE?????????? Hate it when people do that. Also, MAKING SOMETHING REALISTIC SHOULD NOT MAKE IT AN ANTAGONIST.



And so, at the end of the day, this movie will suck visually. Maybe if they use dialogue and the viewers bonding to the characters correctly, they can bring an F to a D, possibly. Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
I'm still kinda irked with this cartoony character design contrasting the gorgeous realistic landscapes. I felt that going with something slightly more realistic like how the land before time would have made the danger and the perils in the adventure even stronger. Every time I see those T. rex onscreen I have a hard time taking them seriously. But other than that looks interesting so far. 

It doesn't seem to have any sort of complex story going on. Most of the focus is on the young Dino getting back to his herd befriending the little boy. Admittedly this isn't the first time these sort of stories have been done but I'm curious to know what else is it going to offer. The relationship between the Dino and his boy have to be strong enough to hold the entire film if that's what it's ultimately going to be about.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
*This movie looks as if it is in the same universe as DreamWorks 'The Croods'.*

Visually, the main difference is that there are now dinosaurs. Also, 'The Good Dinosaur' seem to be more about the perspectives of the beasts, rather than homins.
Speaking of the homin species, this movie seems to be without neanderthals, but just a single homosapien child.


*It is as if the end reveal for 'The Good Dinosaur' is that the boy is actually 'Guy' from 'The Croods'*... Which considering that they look so similar, but with a matter of age differences is not hard to believe... But they are different movies by separate rivalling companies, so that's very unlikely to be the twist.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
Bare in mind that even though this is all hypothetical to where this is a story if the asteroid/comet never hit earth, that single act could have changed and altered many things. Humans probably would have never existed as well as bananas, ect.  It was because of that supposed meteor/comet (or whatever took out the dinosaurs) that brought mass extinction upon the dinosaurs, as well as other plants and organisms, so that the small mammals would have less predators to worry about, thus could thrive and evolve into humans and other recognizable animals.

Another interesting fact is that modern humanoids and dinosaurs could not coexist for one reason; there was much more oxygen on the earth during the dinosaurs' reign. Humans wouldn't be able to breathe the thick O2 if they lived with dinos back before the Cretaceous-Paleogene extinction event and vice versa -- if Dinos lived with us today they wouldn't have enough oxygen to breathe for that's how they evolved to be so large. Humans evolved with the post extinction oxygen levels and most modern plants. Humans weren't always the omnivorous brutes we see today.

Why Pixar chose the whitest looking humanoid to play the homosapien-esque character is beyond me. Depends on what era it is and where they are geographically. Is this before or after the ice age? Is the story set in the Cretaceous/Paleogene era where the continents are still extremely close to each other? Or is it simply based in Africa? Humans just recently migrated out of Africa hundred thousand years ago, which is why there are different skin tones based on sun exposure. So it'd take a while for this little boys' and his people to have such lighter skin than their ancestors for this take place. At least several or more million years after those dinosaurs comically watched the meteor/comet pass by, humans were evolving, born, migrated to cooler climates and then we get the main story we see for any of this to make sense.

But I know... This is just a what if made for fun animated film for kids and a story about friendship. Looks good, I'm gonna see it. Just wanted to point this out if no one already did.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
Wow... No words for how amazing this will be... (Okay, I actually do have some):

It's unbelievable how much animation has changed within twenty years. The details in this trailer are absolutely stunning, and at some points it actually felt like I was watching a movie shot in real life. Then there are those cartoonish looking characters that appeal to audiences of all ages, which is a good thing. Finally, the trailer itself was able to tell a story really without any dialogue. Most trailers we see today need a lot of dialogue to tell what the plot is gonna be for the movie, but this trailer didn't need it. It's a challenge to tell what a movie will be about within a two minute trailer that has minimal dialogue, but of course, Pixar can achieve doing that and even anything.

Comment:
This looks like a cute movie & I HATE 2 be this guy, but it is driving me crazy!- there is literally no way humans & dinosaurs would exist together. The "age of the mammals" was owed to the extinction of the dinosaurs, which opened the pathway, not just 4 our evolution, but the evolution of multiple other organisms 2, such as- wait 4 it- grass & trees! W/ the dinos gone, there were hundreds of niches that needed 2 b occupied: there r no large grazing herbivores? Natural selection gave us bison. Pack carnivores? Wolves. Small arboreal foragers? Squirrels. W/ the continued existence of the dinosaurs, none of the them would exist!

& yes, I do know that there were mammals were around w/ dinosaurs, but the biggest 1 discovered was basically a large flying squirrel. Not that impressive is it?

Comment: Why are you people saying Inside Out was good? There was nothing special about it. I almost fell asleep during the movie because the plot was so weak. It felt like they made a movie for a psychology class rather than a movie with imagination and wonder. Of course, Pixar is basically the only giant in animation in the US because Dreamworks just makes 2 hours of jokes and call it a movie. They make a whole movie out of minions because they want to follow trends of what works instead of just making good movies. Toys coming to life, rats cooking in parisian kitchens, a space romance, those are what sound magical. Inside Out kept moving back and forth from inside Riley's mind to the real world and the plot was all over the place. I love Pete Docter, but let's be honest, it's okay to say Pixar messed up when they don't make a good movie.

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: Gosh, I really hope this Pixar film has potential to be something special, just like A Bug's Life and Monsters Inc.! My question though, is how the hell they're going to sneak the Pizza Planet truck into this film! John Ratzenburger is easy, but the Pizza Planet truck is tough to sneak in each film, especially in an atmosphere like this! Despite that though, I really can't wait for this film, because it'll finally bring us one of the first biggest Pixar milestones in history! TWO PIXAR FILMS IN ONE YEAR, BABY! HELL YEAH! KEEP ON GOING, PIXAR! Inside Out was a masterpiece, but does this film have the potential to top it? I certainly hope so, but just remember, Pixar: Please continue to express the magical messages you've taught children and adults alike over the years, because each and every single Pixar film makes everyone feel like a kid again!

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment: Someone who changed my life? I'll give you multiple. The entire crew at Pixar, their movies have kept me going through multiple bouts of deep depression, & kept me focused on the goal I have of working with them. Finding Nemo taught me to just keep swimming, Monsters University taught me that my dream might work out in a much different way than I thought, Brave helped me to forgive my mom despite being exact opposites, & Inside Out taught me that it's okay to be sad, mad, disgusted, afraid, and joyful. I'm sorry that some people think that Pixar had lost their touch before inside out came out, but to me, they will never lose their touch as long as I live. #gooddino

Title: The Good Dinosaur - Official US Trailer
Comment:
Okay, I will admit, I wasn't too sold on the teaser at first. But after seeing this, I'm actually kinda looking forward to this.

The dinosaurs up-close look a bit too cartoony for my tastes, but from a distance, they look pretty good. The story does seem pretty heartwarming, I'm getting sort of a "Land Before Time" vibe from it. And the animation on the landscapes, water, trees and mountains are absolutely gorgeous. And of course, we have another movie in the Pixar franchise that isn't a sequel.

I gotta say, Pixar: I hope you don't disappoint. :)
